Learning from the Wider World: Adapting Methods from the Tech Industry to Astronomy Research

Astronomy has had a reputation as a field at the forefront of software and data.  However, in many areas over the last few decades, the wider tech industry has developed past astronomy in data volumes and processing requirements.  This implies in astro we can benefit from  spending more time adapting those methods to astronomy's needs rather than developing our own methods.  I will present two case studies of this.  The first example is adapting methods developed for video compression and distribution to astronomy datasets.  While not groundbreaking, such compression methods ave the potential to improve methods used in astronomy for large datasets and, more importantly, require little astronomy-specific development because the underlying software has been developed already. The second is an example of adapting methods developed for Machine Learning and AI to more conventional astronomy spectroscopic reduction and star-finding algorithms, but as a result speeding then up by factos of hundreds or even thousands.  This kind of speedup offers the potential to apply previously intractable forward modeling approaches to larger data contexts like large surveys instead of being limited to small bespoke datasets.  I will end with an outlook on how near-horizon tech developments driven by industry AI may offer new opportunities for astronomy to use AI infrastructure even where astronomy will not actually use generative AI itself.